			<h3 id="format">Teaching format</h3>
			<p>The course includes two semesters of teaching followed by a written dissertation you will complete over the summer.</p>  
			<p>Typically, each module consists of three to five contact hours per week, including:</p> 
			<ul>
				<li>lectures</li> 
				<li>small group tutorials</li>  
				<li>workshops</li>  
				<li>seminars.</li> 
			</ul> 
			<p>The average lecture class size is around 30 students. Larger lectures can go up to 100 students, but are normally supplemented by small group tutorials. Seminar class sizes are usually between 15 and 18 students.</p>  

			<h3 id="coursework-grades">Coursework and grades</h3>
			<p>Assessment for each module is either entirely by coursework, or through a combination of coursework and a two-hour examination and the end of the semester. Coursework may include:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>group presentations or reports</li> 
				<li>case analyses or case studies</li> 
				<li>essays</li> 
				<li>quizzes.</li> 
			</ul>

			<h3 id="study-abroad">Extracurricular learning opportunities</h3>
			<p>The School of Management hosts events and guest lectures throughout the year, providing students with opportunities to socialise and engage with visiting scholars, professionals and practitioners.</p> 
			<p>In addition, the School offers a professional development programme called Masters Extra (MX). This programme includes talks, workshops, networking opportunities, activities and guest lectures from leading academics and experienced managers. </p>

